Swift test-suite
================

This directory contains the SWIG test suite for the Swift target language.

The Swift backend is experimental.  The Swift-specific tests here each ship a
_runme.swift script that exercises a feature of the backend:

  - director_minimal: director support (user-subclassable C++ virtual methods
    via open Swift classes with @convention(c) dispatch functions and
    thread-local exception propagation back to C++).

  - nested_class: nested class and struct support.  Unlike the Python/Ruby
    backends (which hoist nested types to module scope via flatnested), the
    Swift backend generates true Swift inner types so that C++ nested classes
    appear as Outer.Inner in Swift.

  - swift_enums: C/C++ enumerations mapped to Swift enums (raw Int32 values).

  - swift_inherit: single inheritance with C++ virtual dispatch.

  - swift_overload: overloaded free functions and member methods.

  - swift_shared_ptr: objects managed by std::shared_ptr.

  - swift_static: static (class) methods.

  - swift_string: std::string mapped to Swift String.

  - swift_throws: C++ exceptions surfaced as Swift throwing functions.

  - swift_vector: std::vector exposed as a Swift RandomAccessCollection.

Most of the shared SWIG test suite is also generated and compiled; tests not
yet handled by the experimental backend are listed in FAILING_CPP_TESTS /
FAILING_C_TESTS in Makefile.in.

Running the tests
-----------------

From the SWIG root directory (after running ./configure && make):

  make check-swift-test-suite       # run non-broken tests
  make all-swift-test-suite         # run all tests including known failures
  make partialcheck-swift-test-suite  # SWIG generation only, no compilation

The suite always generates the wrappers and compiles the generated C++.  When
configure finds a Swift compiler (swiftc), tests that have a _runme.swift
additionally compile the generated Swift proxy together with the runme and
execute it; configure with --with-swift=/path/to/swiftc to point at a specific
toolchain.  Without a Swift compiler the suite is compile-only, so it still
runs using just the C and C++ compilers used to build SWIG.
